ARIMA(p,d,q) models

In his textbook Rob Hyndman provides the following guide for fitting ARIMA models to data.

  1. Plot the data. Identify any unusual observations.
  2. If necessary, transform the data (using a Box-Cox transformation) to stabilize the variance.
  3. If the data are non-stationary: take first differences of the data until the data are stationary.
  4. Examine the ACF/PACF: Is an AR(p) or MA(q) model appropriate?
  5. Try your chosen model(s), and use the AICc to search for a better model.
  6. Check the residuals from your chosen model by plotting the ACF of the residuals, and doing a portmanteau test of the residuals. If they do not look like white noise, try a modified model.
  7. Once the residuals look like white noise, calculate forecasts.

We’ll use Hyndman’s forecast package to work with ARIMA models. Install the package if you haven’t installed it before (use install.packages()).

library(forecast)
## Warning: package 'forecast' was built under R version 3.2.5
## Loading required package: zoo
## 
## Attaching package: 'zoo'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     as.Date, as.Date.numeric
## Loading required package: timeDate
## This is forecast 7.1

I recommend reading the manual and getting familiar with the package. Here are just a few useful functions in it:

  • The functions Acf() and Pacf() are slight improvements over acf() and pacf().

  • The function Arima() can be used to fit a model with specified values of \(d\), \(p\) and \(q\) to data.

  • The function auto.arima() selects \(d\), \(p\) and \(q\) using a stepwise search. A model using the chosen values is then fit to the data.

  • The function BoxCox.lambda() can be used to select \(\lambda\) for a Box-Cox transformation of the data. The function BoxCox() can be used to transform the data using a selected value of \(\lambda\).

  • The function forecast() can compute forecasts and prediction intervals from ARIMA objects in R. An ARIMA object is the output of functions like arima(), Arima(), auto.arima(), and others.

  • The function ndiffs() uses unit root tests to determine the number of differences required to mae a given time series stationary.

Example 1 - Simulated Data

Let’s generate some data to work with.

set.seed(317)

# white noise
w = arima.sim(n=100, model=list())

# AR(1)
x1 = arima.sim(n=100, model=list(ar=c(-0.3)))

# MA(1)
x2 = arima.sim(n=100, model=list(ma=c(0.2)))

# ARMA(1,1)
x3 = arima.sim(n=100, model=list(ar=c(-0.3), ma=c(0.2)))

# ARIMA(1,1,0)
x4 = arima.sim(n=100, model=list(ar=c(-0.3), order=c(1,1,0)))

# ARIMA(1,1,1)
x5 = arima.sim(n=100, model=list(ar=c(-0.3), ma=c(0.2), order=c(1,1,1)))
  1. Let’s plot the data. Which data sets look stationary?
par(mfrow = c(2,3))
ts.plot(w)
ts.plot(x1)
ts.plot(x2)
ts.plot(x3)
ts.plot(x4)
ts.plot(x5)

  1. For this example tranformations aren’t necessary.

  2. The last two data sets are clearly not stationary. Let’s use the ndiffs() function to check how many differences would make each data set roughly stationary.

ndiffs(w)
## [1] 0
ndiffs(x1)
## [1] 0
ndiffs(x2)
## [1] 0
ndiffs(x3)
## [1] 0
ndiffs(x4)
## [1] 1
ndiffs(x5)
## [1] 1
  1. Here are the ACF and PACF plots of the first four data sets. Based on these plots, what ARMA(p,q) models might you select?
par(mfrow = c(1,2))
Acf(w); Pacf(w)

Acf(x1); Pacf(x1)

Acf(x2); Pacf(x2)

Acf(x3); Pacf(x3)

Now let’s take a look at the ACF and PACF plots of the last two data sets before and after differencing.

par(mfrow = c(1,2))

Acf(x4); Pacf(x4)

Acf(diff(x4)); Pacf(diff(x4))

Acf(x5); Pacf(x5)

Acf(diff(x5)); Pacf(diff(x5))

Notice that this command selected an ARIMA(0,1,1) model instead of the ARIMA(1,1,0) model suggested by the sample ACF and PACF plots. This is because the selection is based on AICc, and the former model has a slightly lower value of the criterion.

  1. Now let’s inspect the residuals of both models. Ideally, they should resemble Gaussian white noise.

First model (ARIMA(0,1,1)):

res1 = fit1$res

par(mfrow=c(2, 2))
ts.plot(res1)
Acf(res1); Pacf(res1)

Box.test(res1, lag=10, type="Ljung")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  res1
## X-squared = 6.7066, df = 10, p-value = 0.7528
par(mfrow=c(1,2))

hist(res1)
qqnorm(res1); qqline(res1)

Second model (ARIMA(0,1,1)):

res2 = fit2$res

par(mfrow=c(2, 2))
ts.plot(res2)
Acf(res2); Pacf(res2)

Box.test(res2, lag=10, type="Ljung")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  res2
## X-squared = 5.1096, df = 10, p-value = 0.8837
par(mfrow=c(1,2))

hist(res2)
qqnorm(res2); qqline(res2)

Example 2 - Temperature Data

temp = read.table("datasets/globTemp.txt", header=T)
y = temp[,2]

Based on preliminary plots, the data clearly is not mean-stationary.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
ts.plot(y)
Acf(y); Pacf(y)

The function ndiffs() suggests taking one difference. The differenced series appear stationary, but the ACF and PACF plots do not reveal a clear choice of model.

ndiffs(y)
## [1] 1
y1 = diff(y)

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
ts.plot(y1)
Acf(y1); Pacf(y1)

We’ll use auto.arima() to fit a model. Note that the chosen model has a drift. This simply means that the ARMA model fit to the differenced data is not zero-mean. Including the option of drift allows for more model flexibility, and might result in the selection of a better model. It can be controlled with the include.drift argument to auto.arima(). By default, include.drift=TRUE, and the function allows for drift.

fit = auto.arima(y); fit
## Series: y 
## ARIMA(0,1,2) with drift         
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ma1      ma2   drift
##       -0.3740  -0.2402  0.0049
## s.e.   0.0726   0.0692  0.0028
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 0.008728:  log likelihood=155.49
## AIC=-302.98   AICc=-302.72   BIC=-290.63

The residuals of this model look roughly like Gaussian white noise.

res = fit$res

par(mfrow=c(2, 2))
ts.plot(res)
Acf(res); Pacf(res)

Box.test(res, lag=10, type="Ljung")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  res
## X-squared = 6.6887, df = 10, p-value = 0.7545
par(mfrow=c(1,2))

hist(res)
qqnorm(res); qqline(res)

We can now compute point and interval forecasts.

plot(forecast(fit, h=7, level=c(80, 95)))
